<refentry xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:ns5="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:scilab="http://www.scilab.org"  xml:id="atan2" xml:lang="en">
    <refnamediv>
        <refname>atan2</refname>
        <refpurpose>4-quadrant inverse tangent</refpurpose>
    </refnamediv>
    <refsynopsisdiv>
        <title>Calling Sequence</title>
        <synopsis>phi = atan2(y, x)</synopsis>
    </refsynopsisdiv>
    <refsection>
        <title>Arguments</title>
        <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>y, x</term>
                <listitem>
                    <para>real scalars, vectors or matrices of the same size.</para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>phi</term>
                <listitem>
                    <para>a real scalar, vector or matrix.</para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <title>Description</title>
        <para>
            <function>atan2(y, x)</function> computes the 4-quadrant arctangent (<function>atan2</function> in
            Fortran), this is, it returns the argument (angle) of the complex number
            <literal>x+i*y</literal>. The range of <code>atan2(y, x)</code> is
            <latex>(-\pi, \pi]</latex>.
        </para>
        <para>In case of vector or matrix arguments, the evaluation is done
            element-wise, so that <varname>phi</varname> is a vector or matrix of the
            same size with <code>phi(i,j) = atan2(y(i, j), x(i, j))</code>.
        </para>
    </refsection>
    <refsection>
        <title>Examples</title>
        <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
x = [1, %i, -1, %i];
phase_x = atan2(imag(x), real(x))

atan2(0, -1)

atan2(-%eps, -1)
 ]]></programlisting>
    </refsection>
